voice_to_text: Not boyfriend said we were not a couple so I broke his heart. We have been seeing each other for a year and everything looked and seemed like we are a couple. He said he loved me and I him. He spends every weekend with me and we have planned our first trip together, etc. Last weekend he was in bed and I made him pancakes because his birthday was on Tuesday. He was very happy about it and joked that I was spoiling him. I said that I wanted to spoil my man. I said I am not your man with the same energy. He didn't seem awkward or embarrassed, just as calm with a smile on his stupid face. I didn't take it seriously and said, yeah, I know you are not my man. He was more serious now and said, no, really, I am not your boyfriend. I felt sick, but I tried to be calm and I asked what we are. He said I don't know. Great FWB. I didn't say anything after that and he ate his pancakes in silence. Later he asked if we would do anything. I said that I was planning on cleaning and doing some paperwork. He left after an hour. I ran to the bathroom to be sick and I probably cried for a solid two hours. I couldn't keep anything in my stomach for the rest of the day. He texted that evening thanking me for the breakfast in Bed and that he thought I was amazing but I didn't answer. So he called a few times. I didn't answer. Around ten PM he rang my door. I just opened a jar and pretended I was sick with the flu and was going to bed. He offered to stay the night in case I needed help during the night and I said no. I didn't answer him on Sunday or Monday, and I didn't wish him a happy birthday on Tuesday either. And I have just been keeping it short text feigning sickness. He never brought up what he said once. Then yesterday he wrote that he missed me and that he hadn't gone this long without talking to me since we met and that he was going mad. He asked if we could at least have dinner. I said that I was very busy. He said don't you miss me? I said that I was very tired because I was out all night with a guy last night. If you don't want to wait for part 2, you can watch the full story on my YouTube channel. Just click on share and then more and then click on the YouTube link here in my profile or search for the Flag Stories Reddit channel on YouTube.

Some guy secrets girls don't know about. I've been keeping this notebook for six years and my girlfriend had no clue until last week. She always said I never opened up emotionally. But honestly, I just thought guys weren't supposed to talk about all the little things they notice. Growing up, my dad forgot everyone's birthday. My mom couldn't remember who liked what food. Their fights were brutal because nobody paid attention to anyone. I swore I'd never be that type of boyfriend. So in college, I started writing stuff down about whoever I was dating. Not weird stalker stuff, just normal things like how Ashley preferred hot chocolate when it rained but iced coffee when it was sunny. Or how Jessica's voice got higher when she was nervous about something. When I met Mia three years ago, the notebook got way more detailed. I wrote down everything, how she stirred her cereal exactly seven times before eating it, how she hummed the same tune when she was happy, how her left eyebrow twitched right before she'd start laughing at something. Every few weeks, I'd add new stuff, like how she only wore her lucky socks on job interview days or how she needed exactly eight minutes of silence when she got home from work before she could handle talking. I wrote down that she liked her apartment at exactly 72 degrees, not 71 or 73, that she always ordered extra pickles but never ate them, that she got cranky If she didn't eat something by 11:00am but never admitted she was hungry, the notebook helped me figure out when to give her space and when to push her to talk about stuff, when to play upbeat music and when she needed something sad. I knew she was stressed when she started reorganizing her bookshelf, so I'd order her favorite Thai food before she even realized she was hungry. When she was upset, she'd clean the bathroom obsessively so I'd run her a bath afterward. None of this felt calculated or weird to me. It just seemed like paying attention. But I never told her about it because it sounded super intense. When I thought about explaining it, like, hey, hey, babe, I've been documenting your behavior patterns for 3 years. Doesn't exactly sound romantic. Plus, guys don't really talk about this stuff with each other. I figured she'd think I was some kind of control freak or something. Last Tuesday, she was cleaning our home office while I was at work. She called me freaking out, asking why I had a notebook with her name on it hidden behind my desk. Panicked, thinking she'd found something embarrassing. But she said she hadn't opened it yet. She was waiting for me to get home to explain. The drive home felt like forever. I kept imagining her thinking I was documenting her flaws or planning to break up with her or something crazy. When I got there, she was sitting on The

I told my sister in law no one cares that she's pregnant. My cousin Rachel just buried her husband and two kids last week. Car accident took them all at once. She's left with just her 5 year old daughter Emma. And honestly, watching them at the funeral was the most heartbreaking thing I've ever seen in my life. So my brother Jake and his wife Kelly show up to our house that morning before we head to the church. First thing Kelly does is announce she's pregnant. We're all getting ready for a funeral. And she's like, guess what, everyone, we have news. My mom congratulated her but told her to keep it quiet for today out of respect. Did Kelly listen? Of course not. The second we get to the church, Kelly starts making these loud gagging noises and rubbing her completely flat stomach. Every time someone looked at her, she'd go, oh, sorry, morning sickness, I'm pregnant. You know, she kept saying stuff like, as a mom, I just can't imagine what Rachel's going through, which was ridiculous because Kelly doesn't have any kids yet. The cemetery, she literally asked Rachel's sister to give up her seat so the pregnant lady could rest her feet. She'd been standing for like 10 minutes total. I was getting so annoyed, but I kept my mouth shut because it's a funeral. After the service, we went back to my aunt's house. Kelly kept making everything about herself. Someone would mention How hard this must be for Rachel. And Kelly would jump in with, oh, I know. Now that I'm pregnant, I understand maternal instincts so much better. When people were talking about the babies who died, Kelly would rub her stomach and talk about how excited she was to be a mom. The bathroom thing was what really got me. Every time Kelly needed to use the bathroom, she'd announce pregnant lady coming through or baby on board needs to pee. There were like 30 people there grieving. And she's treating it like her personal pregnancy announcement party. But then she crossed the line. Rachel was sitting.

My toddler saw a bride taking photos at the park and screamed, don't do it. The bride stopped mid pose. Her photographer looked confused and about 30 wedding guests turned to stare at my three year old daughter Emma standing by the playground swings. I was mortified. Emma had this habit of saying random things loudly at the worst possible moments, but this was next level embarrassing. Ma, honey, let's go play on the slides, I whispered, trying to drag her away from the wedding party, but she wasn't having it. She broke free from my grip and marched right up to the bride, tugging on her dress. Lady, don't marry the mean man, Emma said, pointing directly at the groom. He's gonna hurt you. Everyone went dead silent. The groom's face went red and he started walking toward us looking angry. Hey, what kind of kid says something like that? What are you teaching her? I started apologizing, explaining that Emma was just 3 and had an active imagination. But then the bride knelt down to Emma's level and asked quietly, sweetie, why do you think he's mean? Emma pointed to a bruise on the bride's wrist that was barely covered by her dress sleeve. My mommy had marks like that when the bad man lived with us. She cried at night, too, just like you smell like tears under your makeup. My heart stopped. This kid had been through way too much for her age, but she developed This weird ability to spot things adults tried to hide. When my ex was still around, Emma would always know when I'd been crying, even if I thought I'd covered it up perfectly.

Are you. Are you alive? Yeah, bro. I just had the worst couple days of my life. What? Why? What happened? You know that new diet I've been on, right? Uh, yeah. I heard that eating fiber helps you lose weight. So I got five boxes of those fiber one bars. That's all I've been eating. Nothing else? Just fiber bars. I couldn't the day after that. I did the same thing. I ate six more boxes of fiber bars. Only I didn't that day, either. I was getting very worried. I take at least one on a normal day, but I could feel the fat burning off my body from all the fiber. I didn't the day after that, either. I didn't the fourth day. I didn't the fifth day. I didn't the sixth day. But then I was drinking my morning coffee, and I started hearing the loudest rumble I've ever heard. I thought it was an earthquake or volcano exploding, but no, it was my stomach. I rushed to the toilet. The moment my. Hits the toilet, the loudest and most funkiest fart comes out of my. It took eight seconds for the fart to finish. My mom rushed to the bathroom door. She thought something happened to me. Then it stops. A brick starts to come out, and it's so solid that I feel like I'm giving birth to Megamind out of my. I hung on to the shower curtain and I prayed. I ripped the Whole shower curtain out of the wall. Then the brick finally came out at speeds faster than a F1 racing car. The entire bathroom was soaking in toilet water. That's just the start. A fart that could do more damage than a nuclear missile starts a barrage of bullets from me. After an hour, it seemed to be over. I'm crying at this point, and I can barely breathe. My girlfriend laughed and said, what are you going to do, break up with me? After I caught her texting her ex. I didn't say a word, just walked to the bedroom and started packing. She kept laughing from the couch. You're being dramatic, Michael. It's just texting. I pulled out my laptop, opened my banking app and started clicking. Her laughter died when she heard the notification sounds. What are you doing? Still silent. Removed her from my car insurance, canceled her phone plan that I paid for. Click. Change the Netflix password she used daily. Michael, stop. This isn't funny anymore. But I wasn't done. Logged into our shared Spotify account, change the password. Then Amazon Prime, then Hulu, then Disney plus. Every single subscription she used but never paid for. Even changed the Wi Fi password on our router. Are you seriously going through every account right now? Next, I opened my credit card app, removed her as an authorized user. Then my gym membership, cancelled her guest privileges. My Costco card revoked her access. This is insane. You're being psychotic. I grabbed my suitcase and headed for the door. She jumped up. Panic setting in. Wait, where are you going? You can't just leave. Finally spoke. You asked what I was going to do. I'm showing you. My phone buzzed. Uber outside. Michael, I'm sorry. It meant nothing. Then neither does this. I walked out. The Uber driver was cool, helped me load my stuff without Asking questions. We drove away. I saw her standing in the doorway still holding her dead phone, realizing she couldn't even connect to Wi Fi to call for help. 20 minutes later, my phone exploded. Her number was already disconnected since I'd cancelled the plan. But her friends started texting me. She's crying at Starbucks because she can't call an Uber without her phone plan. She tried to drive home but remembered you took her off insurance. She's asking everyone for Netflix passwords because she was watching a show. She went to the gym and they wouldn't let her in. Then came the really good stuff. Her sister called me. Michael, what did you do? Madison's at my place having a complete meltdown. I did exactly what she suggested. She says you cut off everything, her phone, insurance, streaming accounts, gym access. That's petty. Petty is texting your ex behind your boyfriend's back for two months. Two months, she said. It just started. I sent her sister a screenshot of the oldest text I'd found from March. It was now may. Oh, my God, Michael, I'm so sorry. I had no idea. Her sister called back an hour later. She's been lying to everyone. I read through more of those texts. She was planning to leave you, I know, right after her ex said he wasn't ready for a relationship. So you were her backup plan. Exactly. Keep me around for bills while pursuing him emotionally. The next day I. Got a call from an unknown number. Madison using her mom's phone. Michael, please, I.

My sister said everything I cooked would kill her. So I cooked up something that made her want to die. My sister Meredith discovered the perfect scam when she was 12 years old. She Learned that faking allergies got her whatever she wanted. The first time it happened was at a birthday party. She didn't like the chocolate cake, so she told everyone she was allergic to cocoa. Boom, special vanilla cupcake just for her. By high school, she carried a list of 37 fake allergies, gluten, dairy, shellfish, nuts, red dye, MSG, you name it, she was dying from it. Parents change everything for Meredith's medical needs, special meals, special shopping trips, special everything. Meanwhile, I'd catch her sneaking pizza in her room at midnight, the same pizza that would kill her at dinner. When I got into culinary school, Meredith suddenly couldn't breathe around cooking oil. She'd walk by the kitchen and fall on the floor gasping. Mom made me practice cooking in the garage because Meredith's life was at risk. Opening my food truck should have been the best day of my life. Three years of saving every penny I had. Went into Nora's kitchen first day, lunch rush. There's Meredith. She ordered a salad, took one bite and threw herself on the ground. She was rolling around screaming that I poisoned her, clutching her throat, fake tears, full show. Someone called 9, 1 1. She told the paramedics I put gluten in her food on purpose. The hospital photos went everywhere. Online. My Yelp page got destroyed. People called me a murderer. I had to close for a week, lost thousands in sales. I finally saved enough to open a real restaurant. She did it again. Soft opening night. The place was packed with food critics and investors. Meredith touched a shrimp and went into fake shock. She was thashing on the floor. Her boyfriend, Caleb pretended to give her CPR. Everyone was filming. The health department shut me down the next day. My parents believed every lie. Dad said I should have been more careful. Mom banned me from Sunday dinners because my clothes might have bits of food on them. They spent thousands on fake EP pens while I was drowning in debt. Then came my biggest chance ever. Food Network called. They wanted me for their new show, Rising Star Chefs. Ten years of work LED to this moment. This was everything. Three hours before filming, Meredith called the producers, told them I sent her to the hospital at Thanksgiving by getting food on her plate. She sent fake medical records and to sue. They dropped me instantly. Too much risk, they said. That's when I snapped. Meredith was going to learn what real fear felt like. See, while Meredith faked being scared of food, she had one real fear, mice. Found one in her dollhouse at age 8 and never got over it. Just hearing a squeak made her panic. I started Recording her at her boyfriend's place got weeks of footage. Meredith eating pizza with extra cheese, shrimp with peanut sauce, everything that would supposedly kill her. She was having a feast while ruining my life. I bought 50 mice from a pet store, told them I had hungry snakes. Also bought jars of peanut butter, her deadliest allergy. I texted Meredith about making up over lunch, picked a restaurant across town that specialized in allergy free food. She loved the attention, posted photos about forgiving her sister while she was gone.

What became so popular at your school that the teachers had to ban it? At my school, we created snitch lottery that spiraled into madness. My friend got accused of cheating by this girl who tattled on everyone. We were sick of it. I suggested putting fake confessions in the anonymous tip box. Nothing harmful, just ridiculous things like I'm replacing cafeteria salt with sugar or I'm hiding all the markers. Each Friday when the principal read concerns, we'd silently celebrate. Soon, our whole group was making confessions more outlandish. Each week, word spread and half the school will join. Kids bet on which confession would make assembly. Teams formed to create believable yet impossible scenarios. Things went nuclear when someone confessed to breeding raccoons in the ceiling. The principal called animal control who searched all day. While we tried not to lose it, teachers became paranoid looking for rule breakers who didn't exist. The counselor held meetings about the uptick and bizarre behaviour. The breaking point came when someone wrote about laxatives and faculty coffee. Though it never happened, five teachers called in sick. Next day they traced the handwriting and caught a senior. The principal was livid. They removed the tip box and threatened suspension for fabricating safety concerns. Snitch Lottery died that day, but for two months, we made our boring school believe it was losing its mind.

My ex wife showed up to our divorce hearing pregnant. She thought it would secure her a payout until the judge asked one question. You ever see someone's face when their own lie destroys them? Because I got a front row seat to that exact moment. Natalie walked into that courtroom eight months pregnant, glowing with confidence. She I've been stalling our divorce for a year with every trick in the book, fake emergencies, missing paperwork, sudden mental health crises that required postponements. But this, this was her grand finale. The plan was obvious. Walk in looking vulnerable, play the abandoned pregnant wife card and watch the judge throw out our iron clad prenup out of pure sympathy. He'd done her research, too, picked a female judge thinking the sisterhood would work in her favor. What Natalie didn't realize was that her own paranoia had already destroyed her. Six months earlier during one of our screaming matches, she'd called the cops claiming I'd threatened her. Complete lie. But she ran with it, filed a restraining order. The next day stood in front of a judge with crocodile tears claiming I was violent and dangerous, said she feared for her life and needed protect action. The judge bought it, granted the order immediately. I couldn't come within 500 feet of her, couldn't contact her, couldn't even drive down our old street. My lawyer advised me not to fight it, just let the divorce proceed and move on. So I did. Exactly That followed that restraining order to the letter. Didn't call, didn't text. I didn't even look in her direction when I saw her at the grocery store. I had witnesses, security footage, phone records, everything proving I'd stayed away. But here's the thing about restraining orders that Natalie forgot. They create a paper trail. Every violation gets documented. Every interaction gets recorded. The court system tracks everything. Fast forward to today. Natalie strutted in wearing a designer maternity dress, one hand on her belly, the other clutching tissues for the Waterworks. It even brought her mother. For extra sympathy points, her lawyer started the sob story immediately, painted me as the classic deadbeat dad who'd abandoned his pregnant wife, talked about her financial hardship and how she'd been left with nothing while carrying our child. Natalie sat there, nodding occasionally, dabbing her eyes, playing the victim to perfection. She even threw in protective hand gestures over her belly whenever the lawyer mentioned my name. My lawyer stayed quiet, letting them dig their own grave. When it was his turn, he simply stood up and said, your honour, before we address any financial claims, I believe we need to clarify something important. That's when he pulled out the court records, restraining order application, the sworn statements, the police reports, everything Natalie had filed claiming I was a dangerous monster. The judge reviewed the documents, her expression growing serious. she looked up at Natalie and asked the question that ended everything. Miss Brooks, according to these records, you filed a restraining order.

What's the scariest call you got from school? Girl, when I tell you, I almost fainted when the school called me. I ain't even playing. So it's a regular Thursday. I'm in the middle of target looking for a throw pillow that matches absolutely nothing. And my phone rings. Caller ID says Lincoln Elementary. My stomach drop. I thought, oh, god, did she fall off the monkey bars again? Did she hit someone? Or worse, did she say something? Think she heard me say? So I answer all fake sweet, like, hi, this is her mom. And the lady on the other end says, ma'am, we need you to come in immediately. Your daughter had an incident. Now listen, my daughter Layla is cute, like real cute. Big eyes, big hair, big attitude. She's 8, but she's also part gremlin when she's hungry or bored. So I throw the pillows back, leave the car and speed down to that school like it's the Indie 500. I walk in, heart pounding, and the secretary just points at the principal's office like, yeah, she's in there. I open the door and baby Layla is sitting there with her arms crossed like a little mob boss. Principal looking nervous. There's a boy across from her with an ice pack on his head and a teacher looking like she aged 10 years today. I go, Layla, what did you do? She goes, he tried to take my cookie. So I defended myself. Calm like She's in court. The principal sighs and says she hit him with a lunch tray. I blinked. I'm sorry. She what? Now the teacher jumps in. She told the boy, touch it and you lose a finger. We thought she was joking. Next thing we know, he grabs her cookie and boom, metal tray to the forehead. I had to bite the inside of my cheek to keep from laughing because I know where she got that line, me. She got it from me. I said that last week about my fries at Chili's. But I clear my throat and say, Layla, you can't go around hitting people. He goes, he tried to rob me. What was I supposed to do care? Like it's a fairy tale. That cookie had my name on it in Sharpie. I wrote it. Possession is 9/10 of the law, y'all. She hit him with legal terms. The boy starts sniffling like he's the victim here. And Layla leans in and says, you should have asked. Now look at you. I stocked up like leftovers. I had to turn around and pretend to cough so I wouldn't laugh. I'm dying inside. The principal says, we don't condone violence. Layla goes, neither do I, but I condone consequences. I swear, this child is either gonna be a lawyer or in jail. So I take her home, try to give her a serious talk. I go, he can't be violent. Even if you're right, there's rules. She Goes exactly rule No. 1, don't touch my food. I said, Layla, I'm serious. She goes, okay, okay. Next time I'll use words. Maybe. Probably. And then y'all ready for the kicker? That night, I get a text from the mom of the boy. I'm bracing myself.

Neighborhood crackhead lunged at me so I turned him into a femboy and sold him on Etsy. I live in a sketchy little neighborhood where everyone minds their business except for this one dude. Let's call him Rico. Rico is, well, he's like a local cryptid. No one knows where he lives but he appears at 3:00am yelling about government conspiracies, anime girls and how he once fought a raccoon with his bare hands. Classic Rico. Anyway, last night I'm walking back from the corner store with a bag of Hot Cheetos and chocolate milk living my best trashy life when out of nowhere Rico lunges at me like a feral possum in heat. He's screaming something about me stealing his aura. At this point my fight or flight kicked in and apparently my brain chose black magic. See, I've been dabbling in some alternative arts lately. Long story short, I had a transformation Hex saved on my notes app. Don't ask why, just accept it. So mid lunch I screamed the words, clap my hands together and suddenly poof, Rico is no longer Rico. Rico is now Rianna. Pink crop top, cat ears, thigh high socks, eyeliner sharper than my credit score, the full Femboy starter pack. He blinks, I blink. We both stand there for a solid five seconds like, did that just happen? Fast forward to today and uh, I may have listed him on Etsy under Handcrafted Chaos Beings. Someone from Portland bought him within 3 Minutes for 275 plus shipping. Now I'm sitting here sipping my chocolate milk, trying to process the fact that I may have invented a new side hustle. Before anyone asks, yes, Rico. Now Rianna is thriving. The buyer sent me pics. He's got a made outfit. Now I don't know how to feel.

While I was using the toilet at school, a girl in the next stall asked, can you hop over in here? I need extra hands. Yeah, I don't think so. I wasn't about to climb into a bathroom stall with a freak. No, please. I think I might bleed out. Her voice was shaking. And suddenly this wasn't funny anymore. It was summer from my English class, a pregnant senior who everyone whispered about but nobody really talked to. She was sitting on the toilet, gripping the handicap rail with white knuckles, and her face was covered in sweat. What's wrong? I asked, even though I was starting to guess. Please do something. I'm giving birth. She looked up at me with pure terror in her eyes. My whole body went cold. I was 17 and barely knew how tampons worked, let alone babies. But she was crying and alone, and I couldn't just leave her there. I hopped over the stall divider awkwardly and almost slipped on the wet floor. That's when I saw it. The baby was already crowning. There was blood on the toilet seat and the floor, and summer was making the low groaning sounds that scared me more than anything. This was actually happening in a gross school bathroom with fluorescent lights and graffiti on the walls. I'll be right back. I ran out of the bathroom. Still in shock. I sprinted down the hallway to Missus Bashar's classroom. She was my favourite teacher and The only adult I could think of who wouldn't freak out, I burst through her door, interrupting her lecture on photosynthesis. The whole class stared at me. I need your help urgently, please. I was out of breath and probably looked insane. Missus Bashar took one look at my face and followed me without asking questions. We ran back to the bathroom and I could hear summer sounds getting louder. Other kids were starting to peek out of classrooms wondering what was happening. Missus Bashar pushed open the stall door and immediately went into teacher mode. Okay, honey, I'm here. You're doing great. I'm going to support you while she gets the nurse. I didn't need to be told twice. I ran to the nurse's office faster than I'd ever run in PE. When I burst through the door, Nurse Patty was checking Casey's temperature. Casey, who everyone knew was Summer's boyfriend, the guy who'd been bragging about becoming a dad at prom. Summer's having her baby in the bathroom right now. I basically screamed it. Casey's face went from white to green. He threw up all over the floor before Nurse Patty could grab a trash can. But we didn't have time to deal with that. The three of us ran back to the bathroom with nurse Patty grabbing emergency supplies from her cabinet. By now, half the school had heard something was happening. Kids were crowding outside the bathroom door trying to figure out what all the screaming Was about teachers were trying to move them back to class, but nobody was listening. When we got back to the stall, it was chaos. Missus Bashar was holding Summer's hand while she pushed. The nurse immediately took over, checking how dilated she was and telling summer to breathe. Casey stood frozen in the doorway looking like he might pass out. That's when summer grabbed my hand and pulled me close. You have to get.

When did someone ruin a memory you can't get back? I lost my son to the streets when he was 14. That was it. His dad was in prison, so it was just me working double shifts at the hospital while watching my baby throw his life away piece by piece. But I thought like hell to get him back. I never stopped praying he'd come home alive. That year, everything changed completely. Deshawn got arrested on a weapons charge, facing 10 years as an adult. But the feds made him an offer. Cooperate with their investigation, testify against his crew, and he'd get probation plus witness Protection. Promised me he'd be safe. We've done this hundreds of times, Mrs. Serena. When he was freed eight months later, something was different in his eyes. He looked at me and said, Mama, I'm done with this life. I wanna make you proud for once. The prosecutors relocated us across town. New apartment, new phone numbers, new identities. They said the gang thought he was still locked up. We were completely invisible. When the Howard acceptance letter came in March, full scholarship, he screamed so loud, the neighbors complained. First person in our family to go to university. He was glowing with pure joy and pride. His community college graduation was May 20th. Then Howard in the fall. I took my first vacation day in three years. Bought a new dress from the department store, got my hair done professionally. I wanted to look perfect when they called his name. Deshawn had his speech memorized. Practiced it every morning in the bathroom mirror. The night before graduation, Deshawn was trying on his cap and gown for the hundredth time, practicing his walk across an imaginary stage. I was making his favorite dinner, my grandmother's fried chicken recipe. We stayed up late talking about Howard. He hugged me tight and said, and tomorrow is our day, Mama. We made it. My ex left me pregnant at 17. Now he regrets everything. When Jake knocked me up at 17, he laughed, actually laughed, said my parents will kill me if this ruins my baseball scholarship. Cute, right? Tommy and I basically grew up together. I worked three jobs while getting my nursing degree. Mom watched him when she could. We ate so much ramen that he thought it was a food group. We lived in a tiny shoebox apartment with a couch I bought off Craigslist for $15 and dreams duct taped together. But it worked. By the time Tommy was 10, I was a pediatric ICU nurse and he was this funny, smart, ridiculous little human who made life fun even on two hours of sleep. Then I met Daniel. Daniel's a pediatric surgeon, smart, kind, didn't blink when I told him I had a 10 year old. On our third date, Tommy had a cold and Daniel brought over soup and comic books. I think I fell in love right then. Two years later, we got married and Daniel adopted Tommy. Tommy calls him dad like he Was born to because honestly, he kind of was. We had twin girls three years ago and Tommy is the sweetest big brother. Straight a student, star pitcher for his high school and I mean star college scouts come to see him. Then last month, his team made it to the state championships. I was screaming my lungs out from the bleachers, phone in hand, filming every pitch like a full blown stage, mom. That's when I saw Jake. Same face, just older. He was staring at Tommy like he was.

What's the most rebellious thing you did as a teenager? In my family, there was one rule. I needed my twin's permission to seek medical help. I was watching Vanessa practice her birthday speech when my lungs seized up. I reached for my inhaler on the coffee table, but mom snatched it away. Vanessa, does Ellie need this? My twin didn't even look up from her phone. She used it at lunch. She fine. You heard your sister. Mom dropped my inhaler in her purse. No attention seeking. Today, it's Vanessa's sweet 16th. The rule had been in place since we were 12. The day I faked pneumonia during Vanessa's ballet recital. I hadn't faked it, but Vanessa said I had. So that became the truth. From then on, every headache, every fever, every asthma attack had to be verified by the golden twin. Can't breathe. The wheeze was starting. That whistling sound my doctor called your body's alarm bell, Ellie. Dad's voice boomed from the door. What do we do when you claim you're sick? I knew the script. Ask Vanessa first. And what did Vanessa say? Vanessa finally looked up, annoyed. I said, she's fine. Gosh, Ellie, do you have to make my day about you? My chest was tightening like someone was sitting on it. Breath felt like sucking air through a coffee stirrer. Please, I gasped. Need hospital, mom. Vanessa whined. She's doing it again. Make her stop. Mom rushed to comfort Vanessa. Don't worry, sweetie. Ellie, go to your room. If you're going to act like this, the modelling scout will be here soon. I tried to stand but had to grip the couch. My fingernails were starting to tinge blue. Look, I held up my hands. Vanessa laughed. She probably painted them blue. Remember when she faked passing out at my recital? I hadn't faked it. I had an asthma attack. But Vanessa told everyone I was jealous. So my parents refused to leave her performance. Doorbell rang. Party guests started to arrive. Ellie, disappear. Dad ordered. Vanessa's modelling scout is coming. We don't need you. Wheezing in the background, I couldn't move. My lungs were working overtime, visible through my shirt. Every breath was a battle I was losing. Mom, please, I need hospital, Vanessa. Mom called out sweetly, your sister's asking for the hospital. What do you think, Vanessa? She stood directly in front of me, blocking my parents view. For a second, I saw something flicker in her eyes. She's faking, Vanessa announced loudly. She's just mad. Ted's coming. Ted, my childhood friend who Vanessa stole just because she could. I knew it. Mom shouted, Ellie, stop this immediately. That's when I started coughing blood. Vanessa's best friend, Jenny walked in and froze. Oh, my gosh. What's wrong with Ellie? Nothing Vanessa said. She's being dramatic. Vanessa, she's coughing blood. No, they're not. Vanessa stepped in front of me again. Everything's perfect. Go help with decorations. But Jenny was premed. She Pushed past Vanessa and grabbed my wrist. Her pulse is racing. This is a medical emergency. We don't do medical emergencies without Vanessa's approval. Dad said like it was totally normal house rules. What? Jenny looked horrified. Vanessa knows Ellie best. Mom explained she can tell when Ellie's really sick versus performing. Performing. Jenny was already dialing 9, 1, 1. She's in respiratory failure. Give me that phone, dad lunged.

Not my bedroom door, not the bathroom, not even the closet. Teenagers hide tattoos all over their body if we let them, dad would say, or they could be hiding pills in their pockets. Perfect for 30 second wardrobe changes. I got really good at it too. I kept spare clothes in the bathroom and changed when dad was busy watching TV. Mom would create distractions, calling dad to fix something right when I Needed to change for school. For weeks, this worked perfectly. Dad thought he was enforcing his rules since door stayed open. So I ducked behind my mirror blind spot like always. But Rob didn't know our house layout. He was looking for Dad's office and saw what looked completely wrong from his angle, a teenage girl hiding behind furniture to undress. He looked away immediately but asked me a question that sounded oddly serious. Where's your father? I pointed to Dad's office and he took off through the door. I heard him say, Jim, your daughter was hiding behind furniture to change clothes. Combined with these visibility rules you mentioned, dad came out confused at first. She knows the rules about doors. I froze with the grocery bags in my hands. Through the kitchen window, I could see them all sitting around the table, Mom, Dad and my brother Landon. I told him that at one point he needed to become a man and painting his nails made him look like some sort of weak top. My son and I had never really been close. We didn't even speak that often. So he looked very hurt as I was telling him all this. But I couldn't help it. He had needed a reality check for so long and there was no avoiding this conversation. I told my son to go get nail polish remover and remove his nail polish right there in front of me. Proud of my wife for sticking up to me behind closed doors. And I still felt like I had made the right decision. I won't lie and say that it hasn't been a difficult year. My son stopped talking to me the day I grounded him and I honestly do miss him. He graduates next year and I just hope before then he'll realise that I was only ever trying to do what was best for him.

voice_to_text: My brother got my fiance pregnant, and my dad gave him the family business and a house. So I decided to make them both pay for their betrayal. I found out on a Tuesday. Sophie called in tears, voice shaking so hard I thought someone had died. She sat in her car outside our house, gripping the steering wheel like she was about to crash it. I'm pregnant, she said. For three seconds, I smiled. We've been talking about kids for months. And she added, it might not be yours. Silence. The air around me turned thick. My throat burned. Who? I asked. But I already knew. Her eyes darted away. It wasn't supposed to. Tell me. It's not Alex. The sound she made wasn't even a word. That was all the answer I needed. I staggered out of the car, knees barely working. She chased me, babbling excuses. Late nights. One mistake. She never meant to hurt me. My ears roared. Three months. Four. She swallowed, nodded. I drove straight to the office. My. My brother was there, smug as ever, wearing new Cologne like a cheap disguise. When he saw my face, he knew. Listen, bro, I can explain. My fist landed before the sentence finished. Blood shot from his nose. The room filled with the metallic smell of it, sharp and sour. Dad and two employees pulled me off. Alex shrieked like a coward. She came on to me. We're in love. Those words echoed in the Walls like poison. Mom pressed her hands to her mouth. Janet, our receptionist for 15 years, grabbed her purse and walked out without a word. That silence said more than anything. Dad raised his hands like a judge calling order. His voice was heavy but calm in that fake way he always used when he thought he was the only adult in the room. We'll handle this like adults. Alex spat blood onto the floor, then grinned through it. Teeth red. She's having my baby. You can't ignore that. The room spun. I looked at dad, he looked at Alex, then at me. We'll figure this out. Family is family. I left a week later.

voice_to_text: My new manager fired me in front of the entire restaurant. But Karma served him something he couldn't swallow. Carlos showed up at Rose's Cantina in February with his restaurant management certificate, and right away he started changing everything we've been doing for years. He walked around with a smug attitude, telling everyone the kitchen was disorganized and that we needed to follow modern systems instead of the old ways. After two months of his nonsense, he called me into the main dining room while the whole lunch crew was watching. Miguel, we need to make some changes around here, he announced loud enough for everyone to hear. You refused to follow corporate procedures, so I'm letting you go. You're done. Clear out your things. I've been the head cook at roses for 12 years, and I knew every single regular customer by name and exactly how they like their food. But I just nodded quietly and went to get my stuff. The waitresses all stood there frozen. And Elena, who'd been there almost as long as he, had tears running down her face. As I was walking out with my things, I stopped and said over my shoulder, hope the weekend breakfast rush goes smooth for you. Carlos just waved his hand like it didn't matter. Any trained cook can handle eggs and beans, smiled to myself, Mother's Day weekend is coming up. Should be interesting. His confident expression flickered for just a second. What about Mother's Day? Oh, Nothing special, I said, heading for the door. Just our busiest three days of the year. All the families come in with their special orders. You'll be fine. What Carlos didn't know was that Mother's Day weekend at roses was like the Super Bowl for us. Families would pack the place from Friday through Sunday and every single regular family had their own special way they wanted their breakfast. I've been preparing special seasoned meats for weeks that customers have been asking about, marinating them just right with my own blend of spices I perfected over the years. Carlos had never bothered to learn any of this stuff because he was too busy talking about portion control and standardized recipes. Our customers were families who'd been coming for generations and wanted their food exactly how they remembered it from when their parents brought them as kids. Saturday morning came and at 6:00am sharp, my phone started going off. I ignored it and made myself some coffee. By 6:45, Carlos had called eight times. At 7:15, Elena texted me.

Mom was so happy. She kept saying maybe the cancer was a blessing because it brought her son back to her. I wanted to believe it, too. I really did. One afternoon, I came by to drop off her prescriptions and found mom sitting on her bed crying. Not like normal sad crying, but that silent kind where you're too shocked to make noise. Her hands were shaking, and her laptop was open in front of her. I asked what was wrong, and she just pointed at the screen. Her bank account was pulled up. The balance said $312. Should have been almost 40,000. Her entire savings, the money she'd been putting away for 30 years. Gone. She kept saying maybe it was a scam. Maybe someone hacked her account. Maybe the bank made a mistake. But I knew. I grabbed her phone and logged into her banking app and scrolled through the transactions. Sports betting sites, hotel rooms in Vegas, bars charging 400 bucks at once. All of it had Ethan's card linked to her account. I felt sick. I screenshotted everything, printed it at her house. And we waited for him to show up that evening, like he'd been doing when he walked in with his stupid flowers. Mom asked him straight up if he took her money. And he didn't even lie. He didn't even pretend. He just shrugged and said, yeah, he'd been using it. Then he looked at her dying in her own bed, and Said you were gonna die anyway. At least I got to actually enjoy it. I've never seen my mom's face do that before. It was like watching her heartbreak in real time. She told him to get out. He laughed and said she'd forgive him by next week, like she always did. But she didn't. She told me to change every password, every login, everything. I called the police that same night. Mom didn't want to press charges. She said she couldn't send her own son to jail, even after what he did. But she called her lawyer the next morning and removed him from her will completely. Every single thing went to me. She made sure it was airtight so he couldn't contest it.

The balance said 3 hundred and twelve dollars. It should have been almost 40,000. Her entire savings. The money she'd been putting away for 30 years. Gone. She kept saying maybe it was a scam. Maybe someone hacked her account.

Oh, yeah? We talked for an hour, laughed. His hand brushed mine.

I made a scene of my adult son and stick my nose in his marriage. My daughter in law called me Thursday night and I could hear her voice crack. Before she even said anything. She told me she couldn't make it to the spa weekend we paid for because my son decided his friend was in town and he wanted to hang out with them instead. Just like that, her birthday weekend gone. I already noticed she looked exhausted last time I visited. Three kids under four years old and she's doing everything alone. My son convinced her to quit her job and stay home by selling her this perfect picture of family life. What he didn't tell her was that when I stayed home with him, his dad and I split everything 50 50. After five, I got Sundays off, I got date nights twice a week. She gets nothing. So I pushed a little, asked how things really were. She broke down and told me everything. He doesn't help with the kids, doesn't do chores, doesn't take her out. Just sits there acting like she's supposed to handle three babies alone. Because that's what stay at home moms do. I was so angry I could barely think straight. I told her to drop the kids with me, bring a friend to the spa. And I gave her 500 euros from my savings to buy herself something nice. She cried and thanked me. Then I made her tell Me. Where my son was. Me! Five minutes of begging, but she finally said he was at Murphy's Bar downtown. The second she left for the spa, I grabbed my keys and drove straight there. Found him and his buddies in the back corner, laughing and drinking like he didn't have a care in the world. I sat down right next to their table. His friends went quiet first. Then he looked up and saw me. I said loud enough for the whole group to hear, did I fail you as a mother, or was it your father? Because we both thought you were supposed to put your partner first, not your drunk friends. His face went red immediately. One of his buddies mumbled something and got up to leave. I kept going. Told him his wife is home alone every single day with three kids while he's out here acting like he's still 20. Told him I didn't raise him to treat people like this. Told him his father would be ashamed. He tried to tell me to leave, said I was embarrassing him. I said, good. Maybe he should be embarrassed. The bartender came over and told me I needed to go. I told my son he better fix this or he'd lose everything. Then I left. Got banned from the bar on my way out.

My wife sent me a text. I need one week to think if you're worth keeping. So I gave her lifetime to think. We've been married six years. Most men would panic call immediately, beg for clarity. But as I read those words, something clicked. She wasn't asking for space. She was giving me an expiration date, like I was some product she wasn't sure about purchasing. I right back. Take all the time you need. I'll be using mine productively. That's it? No questions. You've made your position clear. Instead of desperate messages, I opened my laptop and made changes. Called our bank, removed her as authorized user from joint credit cards, changed passwords on Netflix, shopping accounts, cloud storage. My phone buzzed. What did you do to the Netflix? Prioritizing my expenses during your evaluation period. Are you serious? Dead serious. You want to evaluate my worth, do it without using my resources. For months, I'd felt like she saw me as convenience rather than partner. Dismissing my opinions, making plans without consulting me, eye rolls at my suggestion. This text was someone calculating whether benefits outweighed cost. When I got home, she was waiting. We should talk. About what? Cutting off my cards? Changing password? That's a stream. I looked at her directly. You're spending a week deciding if I'm worth keeping? Hard to evaluate someone's value while actively using their resources. That's not what I meant. Then you should have been more specific. That night, I Researched voice attorney. A man who knows his worth doesn't wait around hoping someone else will recognize it the next morning. When I said I needed time, I meant we should both evaluate where we are. Your text mentioned thinking whether I'm worth keeping. Nothing about mutual evaluation by Thursday. She was desperate. I came home to find her with Derek from yoga class. Tall guy, expensive.

What's your worst experience with the healthcare system? When my wife was pregnant with our twin boys, the doctors somehow missed her pulmonary hypertension, a heart condition that kills 30% of mothers in labour. We didn't even know she had it till she gave birth 12 weeks early and ended up in a coma. Even worse, when our boys came out, they were blue in the face and needed the N I C U. Immediately for any chance of survival. But apparently the hospital couldn't put them in the N I C U. They needed insurance authorization from our providers before saving their lives. I told her that would take days, and my boys were literally purple. But the woman just sighed. I'm sorry, but rules are rules. Without authorization, we're talking about a 4 hundred thousand dollar Bill you'd be personally liable for, she said, not even looking at my twins. I could hear the heart monitors going crazy. Please, I begged, dropping to my knees. Look at them. Look at them! They're dying. She glanced over for half a second. Sir, getting emotional won't change protocol. I suggest you call your insurance company. I fumbled with my phone, hands shaking so bad I could barely dial. The insurance company put me on hold while my babies were turning darker blue. Twenty minutes of that cheerful hold music while I watched my son Lucas's heart rate drop from 180 to 140 to 110. The administrator, Mrs. Miles, was at Her desk, eating a sandwich. I ran over. Phone still on hold. Please, just start the treatment. I'll pay cash. I'll sell my house. I'll sign anything. Sir, even if you had $400,000 cash right now, we can't accept it without going through insurance first. It's fraud prevention protocol. She took another bite of her sandwich. A young nurse finally broke. Missus miles, those babies have maybe an hour. Jennifer, you're already on probation. One more word and you're fired. The nurse shut up, but she was sobbing. Other parents in the waiting room were recording on their phones. Horrified. One dad stood up and said, lady, what is wrong with you? Missus miles called security. I need these disruptive individuals removed from the admin area. I ran back to my boys. Ethan wasn't moving anymore.

My siblings and I sat at dinner when our father smiled and asked, ready to compete for the upstairs bedroom? Again? I stared in shock. Again? I don't want to compete. Oh, sweetie, mom said, reaching across the table to pat my hand. The monthly room assignment builds character. Winners get the master suite. Losers get the basement. My younger brother, Marvin, pushed his food around his plate. My sister Bianca, wouldn't even look up. We've been doing this for three months since we moved to this house. The basement had exposed pipes, no heat, and spiders that dropped from the ceiling at night. Bianca won last month with her debate trophy. Dad continued, pulling out his notebook. So she keeps the room unless one of you beats her achievements this month. The chicken tasted like cardboard in my mouth. This is insane. Other families don't do this. Mom's smile tightened. Other families raise weak children. We're raising winners. That night, Bianca came to my basement corner, where I'd hung sheets for privacy. I'm sorry, she whispered. I didn't want to win, but sleeping down here made me sick last time. It's not your fault, I said, but the words felt hollow. Marvin had already stopped talking to both of us. Next morning, dad posted the point chart on the refrigerator. 10 points for A's, 20 for sports victories, 15 for volunteer hours, even five points for who said good morning first. I watched Marvin set his alarm for four A M. Just to beat us to the kitchen. By week two, Bianca started hiding my homework. I found it crumpled in the trash after getting a zero. Marvin put a dead spider in my backpack during lunch, making me scream in front of everyone. We stopped eating together, stopped helping each other with assignments. Three kids living in the same house, acting like enemies. Look, get that competitive spirit! Dad beamed. One morning, after Marvin and Bianca physically fought over who got to take out the trash for points. Mom took photos like it was something to be proud of. My grades started slipping from the stress. I couldn't sleep in the freezing basement, constantly checking for spiders. Bianca developed anxiety.

When did the loser sibling finally win? I spent my childhood digging through trash cans for the toys my brother Macky threw away. He always got everything new while I got his scraps. For Christmas, I had to watch Macky open a second new Tamagotchi in case the first one dies, while I was left with a dead one that had a screen so scratched you couldn't see the pet, even if it did somehow work. Even on my 10th birthday, when I begged for a Game Boy Advance, my family handed me Macky's old Game Boy color with a scratched that barely worked. It's too expensive, they said, only to buy Mackie a GBA a week later. I tried to complain about it, but my parents immediately shut me down saying, why waste money when your brother's old one works perfectly fine? And each time he gets something new I just find it in the trash a week later. It's for babies, he would tell me. But when I found his entire card collection in the trash can, thrown out and forgotten like how my parents pretty much did with me, I actually felt excited. It was like digging up treasure. I looked around and grabbed it, cleaned up his old premium binder and admired the restoration. Welcome to the family, I said. The cards! Before storing it away safely. After that, I fell in love with restoring and collecting everything Macky threw out. I kept things in their Cases so they wouldn't get dusty, made acrylic boxes for other toys, and even saved all my allowance just to buy a limited edition binder for the Pokemon cards. I. I joined a few online forum groups for toy collectors and picked up on how to restore the dead Tamagotchi and repair the screen. When it started working, I grinned and shared it online. Everyone applauded me, wishing their kids took care of their toys like me. And over the years I ended up making a lot of friends from these groups, all nerds and geeks who his rooms look like vintage museums. So when Mackey continued mocking me saying your room looks like you're 5, grow up already! It didn't even bother me anymore. Ten years later, the communities I joined became massively popular. The collection I started when I was just six ended up being worth more than a fancy full paid house. But I never sold any of it. Not even when my brother mocked me for having a room that deflected girls or when my parents shamed me for buying toys at my age. Ironically, my brother Mackie ended up having kids of his own that were obsessed with Pokemon cards just like he used to be. They wouldn't.

The waiting room was full of other families in various states of distress, all seemingly forgotten by the staff, who walked past us like we were furniture. At this point, I checked room after room until I found her. My mother. Lying on an examination table, completely alone. No monitors attached, no IV. Her skin was completely gray. Laying there completely unattended. I knew immediately what I was looking at. She was having heart problems for years. And exactly what it was. Mom was having a heart attack. And no one was doing anything about it. A nurse burst in behind me, young and flustered. Sir, you cannot be in here. This is a restricted area. I pointed at my mother's

What's the most elaborate prank someone planned from their deathbed? My Uncle Harold called me to his hospital bed three days before he died and handed me a thick envelope. Open this. At my funeral. During the eulogy, he wheezed that familiar mischief in his eyes. Promise me, Timothy, when your father starts talking about what a disappointment I was. I promised, though I should have known better. Harold was the family failure. Never married, no kids, lived in a trailer, worked odd jobs. My father and aunts constantly reminded him how he'd wasted his potential. Every family gathering ended with someone lecturing Harold about responsibility, while he just smiled and nodded. When he got cancer, they suddenly cared, hovering around his hospital bed, asking about his affairs and whether he'd made arrangements. The funeral was exactly what Harold predicted. My father stood at the podium, going on about missed opportunities and poor choices, barely disguising his contempt as grief. That's when I opened the envelope. Inside was a single page and a USB drive labeled Play Me Now. I walked to the funeral home's AV system and plugged it in. Harold appeared on screen, very much alive, sitting in his hospital bed, grinning. Hello, family. If you're watching this, William just finished explaining what a loser I was. Time for some truth. My father went pale. First, let's discuss money, since you're all wondering what happened to mine. William, remember when dad left me $50,000 and you convinced Me to invest it in your restaurant. The one that mysteriously burned down? I know you torched it for insurance money. I have the security footage. Gasps filled the room. My father started toward the screen, but froze when Harold continued. Patricia, sweet sister. You've been stealing from Mom's nursing home account for six years. I have the bank records. Already sent them to the authorities yesterday, so expect a visit soon. My aunt Patricia ran for the door, but two police officers were already walking in. Gordon, baby brother. What's the most life changing thing a kid has ever said to you? I never wanted kids. Not because I didn't like them. I just never pictured myself as a parent. My life was simple. Wake up, go to work, come home, repeat. But that all changed because of my neighbor's son. After his mom, Maya, got injured in a car crash, I started driving her eight year old son, Lucas, to school. It I was on my way to work anyway, and she had no one else to help. At the time, Lucas was a quiet kid, polite, always clutching a backpack that looked bigger than him. But once he got comfortable, he talked my ear off about dinosaurs. Every morning it was some new fact about T. Rexes or velociraptors. Started googling Dinosaur facts at night just so I could keep up with him. The way his whole face lit up when I remembered the names made it feel worth it. One morning, he didn't say much. We were halfway to school before I noticed the silence. I asked if he was okay, and he said some kids had made fun of him because he didn't have a dad coming to career day. He tried to brush it off, but I saw the tears building in his eyes. He was trying to act tough, but it was breaking him. Without even thinking, I offered to go. I told him I was just a mechanic, nothing special. But if He wanted I could bring in some car parts and talk about engines. His eyes lit up like I had offered to bring a spaceship. That week, I showed up with tools, heart, and a demo board. I explained to a room full of third graders how engines work, how spark plugs fire, how fuel turns into power. They loved it. But Lucas sat in the front row, hands on his knees, grinning like he'd been waiting for this moment his whole life. Every time I asked a question, his hand shot up. He already knew the answers. After school, he hugged me. Then he leaned in close and whispered, I wish you were my dad. I didn't know what to say. That night, Maya called to thank me. We ended up talking for hours about everything. Our lives, our regrets, our dreams. How sometimes the best families are the ones that find each other. Two years later, Lucas stood next to me as the best man at our wedding. In his speech, he said, I knew you'd be my dad the day you Learned about

The mall cop pulled me into the security office and said, your photo is on every exit door. We need to move right now. I looked at him confused, because Gary usually just sat at his desk, watching monitors and eating chip. He's been working at Westfield Mall for, like, eight years and only ever told kids to stop running or get off the fountain edge. What do you mean? I pulled away from his grip, but he held tighter. There on his desk were printouts of my school photo taped to every monitor. My face was everywhere. Gary locked the office door and pulled down the blinds so fast, one of them bent away from the windows. His hands were shaking as he picked up his radio. This is some kind of mistake, right? I tried to laugh, but it came out wrong. Maybe someone thinks I shoplifted or something. Gary wasn't listening. He was punching numbers into his desk phone using some kind of code. Alpha 7 7. Requesting immediate federal backup. Confirm visual on the target. The target? That's when I noticed the monitors showing them all corridors. Men in dark suits were spreading out through the food court. They weren't shopping. They were searching. I need to call my parents. I pulled out my phone, but my dad's number went straight to a disconnected message. Not voicemail, just disconnected. I tried again. Same thing. My mom picked up on the third ring, but her voice sounded Wrong. Strangled. Honey, where are you right now? She was trying to sound calm, but I could tell she'd been crying. I'm at the mall with Emma. Mom, what's going on? There was silence for a few seconds, and I heard muffled voices in the background. Male voices. Stay exactly where you are. Don't leave that office. Don't trust anyone except the guard. The line went dead. I tried calling back, but now her phone was disconnected, too. Gary was watching the monitors, and his face had gone pale. They're at every entrance. 12 of them at least. Who? Who's at every entrance? I moved closer to look at the screens. The men in suits were showing something to store employees. My photo. They had my photo. Gary pulled open his desk drawer and took out a gun. An actual gun? I didn't even know mall security could have guns. He checked if it was loaded and set it on the desk within reach. Listen, kid, I got a federal alert.

The mechanic fixing my car asked me, did your dad buy this used from someone local? Yeah, he bought it from some guy on Craigslist about three months ago, but I'm the one who drives it mostly now, since I just got my license. The mechanic wiped his hands on a rag and walked me around to the front of my Subaru Legacy while my dad waited in the shop's lobby, scrolling through his phone, probably answering work emails. He brought the car in for a simple oil change, but the mechanic had been under there for way longer than normal, and now his face looked like someone had died. He popped the hood and pointed a flashlight at something underneath that I couldn't really see from where I was standing, but his hand was trembling. You need to get your dad over here right now. And nobody drives this car again until we fix this. His voice was steady, but there was something in his eyes that made my stomach drop. Like when you miss a step going downstairs. Someone wanted you dead, and they almost succeed. Another day or two of driving this thing and you wouldn't be standing here. What's wrong with it? I asked while texting my dad to come outside immediately. But the mechanic was already taking pictures with his phone and muttering about calling the police, which made no sense for a car repair. My dad pushed through the door, looking annoyed because he'd Been in the middle of a work haul. But his expression changed when he saw the mechanic's face. The mechanic grabbed a trouble light and aimed it at the brake lines near the master cylinder, showing us cuts that went almost all the way through the metal. These were sliced to leak slowly over weeks. So when they finally failed, it would look like a tragic act. Accident that nobody would question. He moved the light to show three different cut points, all at calculated angles that would have failed simultaneously. Professional job. But they made one mistake. They used a specific cutting pattern I've only seen once before. My dad's face went white as he stared at the sabotaged brake lines. And I remembered last week when I'd slam the brakes to avoid a dog. And felt them go completely.

My golden child stepbrother attacked me because I wouldn't give him money. But I recorded everything and sent him straight to jail. My entire childhood is filled with memories of my elder brother being coddled by my family. My parents are very traditional, and they were certain that my brother would take care of them, while I would turn out to be a failure. They would take him to the movies, but tell me that I needed to stay home and study. I remember he got the new Game Boy for his eighth birthday, and I wanted the same thing because he would never share it. But when I asked for a gift, they grounded me because demanding things is not a good attitude. Ever since then, I became scared to ask for anything. I had to go to bed hungry one time because no one called me for dinner, and I was too afraid to ask for food. This one time, when we were around 13, he kicked a football and smashed one of the windows in our house. He knew that our dad was very strict about playing football inside, so he told them that it was me who broke the window. I tried explaining that I was hanging out with my friends at the time, but they didn't believe me. I was grounded to my room for an entire week. All my toys were taken from me. By the time I entered high school, I was practically Ignoring everyone at home and focusing on finding a job. That's because my parents had made it clear that they would sponsor my brother's college tuition, but not mine. So if I wanted to get further education, I needed to save up for it on my own. So I started balancing my school life alongside a job in retail. Fortunately, I met some friends in high school with whom I later started a business. When I turned 18, my parents kicked me out of their house, so I went to live with one of those friends. I use the money I saved up for college to invest in our business, and thankfully, it became successful. Now I just bought a new house and held a Celebration to which I invited all my friends and family who supported me. My parents and my brother were not invited. However, my brother somehow found my address and showed up to the party in a suit.

Don't wait up. My husband texted. The locksmith didn't either. It was eleven thirty PM on a Thursday when I got that text from Ryan. He'd been working late again. Third time this week. Said he had to finish some project for his boss. I was already in bed watching Netflix on my laptop, wearing his old college T-shirt that still smelled like his Cologne. The thing is, I wasn't planning on staying up anyway. But around midnight, I heard footsteps on our front porch. Heavy boots. Like work boots. Figured Ryan forgot his keys again, which happened way too often for a 28 year old man. I paused my show and waited for him to knock. Instead, I heard metal clicking. Sounds like someone was picking the lock. My heart started racing. I grabbed my phone and crept to the bedroom window that faces our front door. There was a guy I'd never seen before hunched over our doorknob with some weird tools. He had a baseball cap pulled low and was wearing a dark jacket. I called 9 1 1, immediately whispered to the operator that someone was breaking into my house. She told me to stay hidden and quiet, that police were on their way. The whole time I'm watching this guy work on our lock like he owns the place. Then the front door opened. But here's the crazy part. The guy didn't sneak in like a burglar. He just walked in normally, turned on the Living room lights. And started looking around like he was shopping for furniture. He even checked his phone and made himself comfortable on our couch. Five minutes later, I heard another car pull up through the window. I saw Ryan getting out of his Honda. But instead of looking surprised or scared that our house lights were on, he walked right up to the front door like nothing was wrong. The locksmith guy let him in. They shook hands like old friends. That's when it clicked. Ryan had hired this guy to break into our own house. But why? We both had keys. I had a spare hidden under the fake rock by our mailbox that he knew about. I stayed hidden in the bedroom and

Courtroom in another white outfit, because apparently she didn't learn her lesson. Dabbing her eyes with a handkerchief and shooting me these dramatic looks like I'm some kind of monster. He's describing how I supposedly commanded security guards to physically assault a defenseless 58 year old woman, how they threw her to the ground with excessive force, causing traumatic brain injury and permanent psychological damage. The whole time I'm sitting there thinking this has to be some kind of elaborate prank. Except the judge looks dead serious, and Patricia's lawyer just pulled out medical records. I brought my laptop and asked if I could connect it to courtroom's TV screen. The judge nodded, probably curious about what actually happened. The first video showed Patricia entering the venue in her white gown, guests visibly confused, some taking pictures because they couldn't believe it. The third video, the important one, showed the security guards approaching Patricia with their hands visible and relaxed of them saying, ma'am, we need to ask you to leave. Please come with us. In the most professional Voice ever. Patricia screamed at them, but they never touched her, just gestured toward the exit and walked beside her, maintaining three feet of distance. Fourth video from the parking lot camera showed the real story. Patricia storming out, the guards standing by the door watching her leave, and then Patricia turning to scream something at them, spinning on her heel, dramatically catching her dress on her own shoe, and face planting into the concrete completely unassisted while the guards were 15 feet away. Yep. Patricia tripped and fell and then sued me.
